"""# Task 5: The `format` Function Part 2

Prompt the user to enter two values - a string and an integer.  Using these values generate output that looks like the following:

**Example Run #1:**

```
Enter a word: pikachu
Enter an integer: 25
*************************
                  pikachu
         pikachu         
pikachu                  
*************************
```

**Example Run #2**

```
Enter a word: CRAIG
Enter an integer: 50
**************************************************
                                             CRAIG
                      CRAIG                       
CRAIG                                             
**************************************************
```

The length of each line of stars should match the integer supplied. For example, if the user enters the number 25 you should display 25 stars.

When displaying the name you will need to align the name to the right, center and left within the boundaries set up by the starred lines. 

You can alwasy assume that the integer provided will be at least 3x as large as the length of the supplied word (i.e. the word "apple" has 5 characters, so the integer supplied will be >= 15)

Hint: the format function takes two arguments - the value you are formatting and a specifier which describes how to format that value.  The specifier is a string (i.e. '>20s') - can you think of a way to get the value supplied by the user into this string?
"""

# write your code here
word = input("enter a word:")
integer = int(input("enter a number:"))

print("Enter a word:", word)
print("Enter an integer:", integer)
print("*"*integer)
print(format(word, ">"+str(integer)+"s"))
print(format(word, "^"+str(integer)+"s"))
print(word)
print("*"*integer)

